"Like nothing you've even seen be-fur"
While I agree that that was an excellent pun, one that Sans would approve of, and I have yet to see the movie, but wouldn't it be at least a LITTLE bit similar to Disney's Robin Hood, Disney's The Jungle Book, Disney's The Lion King, maybe even a little bit like Dreamworks' Madagascar?

Also, I'm pretty sure its statistically impossible for something to be like "Nothing you've ever seen be-fur" because every idea ever comes from our brains taking stuff we've seen and jumbling them up into something new, making it statistically impossible for anything made or done by man to be absolutely NOTHING like anything else...
And statistically unlikely for something to be nothing like someone has seen before. But still, that phrase, as good a pun as it is, is still incorrect because it is saying that to millions of people, meaning it can't ALWAYS be correct...

Most importantly, the story is really good. I watched a lot of animated film and most of the time end up having the conclusion of "the story line is too simple, meh.. it's for kids"
But this one, I think adult will love it too.  Totally recommending it!!

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment: 1. Saw the movie. You should see it too.2. Why does everyone say this is a furry movie? I don't get it. They say that the animals walk on two legs, wear clothes, use technology, act like humans do, and that apparently makes them furries. Y'know what other characters match that exact description? Mickey Mouse, Goofy, and Donald, to name a few. Yet I don't see people freaking out over why they are furries, and need to burn and stuff. Now, this part is for the furries. Honestly, I don't get why you do what you do, but hey, if it helps you out in some way, allows you to meet other people with confidence, knock yourself out. I mainly have a problem with the obsessive furries known as "furfags." First time I saw this teaser was last year when I saw Inside Out in theaters. The minute the word anthropomorphic came on the screen, I knew the crazy furries would be all over, and that the Zootopia tags on Instagram, Tumblr, etc. would be overflowing with posts mentioning, "yay a furry movie im so happy" and I was right. By now, I realize that posting this may or may not start a flame war, but I'm too deep in now. Basically, stop associating this movie with furries or calling this movie a furry movie. It's simply a nice Disney movie for families, with animals that walk and talk, which Disney has been doing before any of you were born. I now await the strongly written replies below. Just try to be respectful to one another, okay? Like I said, it's a family movie, so kids might be on here.

if anthropomorphic means animals that wears cloths, walk on two feet, and use modern technology does that mean that humans are anthropomorphic as well.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment:
I really wish Disney would make another hand-drawn movie... Now, i'm not saying that 3D animation is bad or anything but the market is saturated by it and it would be really refreshing to see hand-drawn again... Especially from a giant like Disney that has such a rich history with hand-drawn... I get that some movies will probably look better 3D animated (like Tangled with Rapunzel's hair) but i don't think it is crucial for Zootopia (ok, maybe a little with the fur and all) or especially Moana. I'm worried that Disney has abandoned hand-drawn after the Princess and the Frog flop box-office-wise. In my opinion it looks absolutely stunning and the story and music are amazing!
But what can i do? Market and money will always dictate the course of a company, which is why we should support Disney and go to theatres and buy dvds especially when a hand-drawn movie comes out. Really people, do it! Let's bring back Disney hand-drawn. It's all up to us, we create the market!

Hm not sure if okay or piss about this. Reason for piss is I am not 100% sure but they might have taken some minor ideas from a webcomic called zoophobia by a artist called vivziepop and thats been here bit longer before they announce this with concept art while back. 
So for ppl reading and wondering what is zoophobia this how it goes. Zoophobia is a hidden city filled with animals and then the 2 similarities are the animals and city are there. What's different is in zoophobia the animals that talk have the ability to shift into human form or cross between that (example deer looks like a boy but with deer ears and some small antlers) or a anthro form of it like shown with characters here. Some humans also exist in this city if chosen to become a resident. Also coexist in the city are demonic and monster like characters but most of them are good and if you read the webcomic it explains how they live together. 
Now here is they are all anthro form, no humans, demons and monsters and its target is for kids while zoophobia is a bit 16+ age range (some violence and language in it). So again I am not sure if they took some minor ideas from it but just saying when this gets popular and ppl find out about zoophobia and be idiots saying the artist took ideas from this she didn't. Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment: There is a pretty bad stigma surrounding the community, but honestly, furries are about the nicest people I have ever met. They also party hard, too. In very much the same way that all fandoms gain their outside image from the worst of the worst (ie. bronies and fat fedora-wearing Hot Topic shoppers), furries gain their recognition from the copious amounts of porn that come from the 0.01% of the community. Sure, there's a few weird grapes in the bunch, but they should definitely not be the main image given to the hundreds of thousands of varying representatives. Of course you're going to hear the worst parts about any fandom; scandalous news sells the most. What you may find, however, is just a bunch of friendly people gathering and sharing the same interests. In fact, go ahead and shed light on the subject yourself; toss out what you know about furries and try out the community. Introduce yourself on forums, attend a convention, join a meet-up, whatever.

Comment:
Furry here, i have something to say to the "haters" and "anti-furries" and also to "furries" like me.
First: This movie is the perfect opportunity for us to talk like civilized people about our differences, so don't screw this up by defending your postures blindly, be smart and listen.
Second: This movie is NOT aimed for furries only, Disney knows that following the furry identity they can get free advertising and hype, because we will talk about this for months, i'm sure. The reason Disney is using anthropomorphic animals as protagonists and giving it so much importance is for the secondary plot, the part about discrimination between species and because kids love animals.
Third: Yes, this furry hype will end in a lot of people interested in the furry fandom. You can do nothing about that, you can't sink furries image, you will only expose yourself as a discriminative ignorant by trying it.
In conclusion: ignore the fact that furries will love this movie, just stop talking about that. And for the furries, stop saying "i love this movie because i'm furry" nobody cares if you are a furry, that's not making you a more interesting person, so shut up about that.
If we can talk about how well made are the characters and if we can say or opinions about the plot, i will be really happy, because i think i'll enjoy this movie.

Comment: As some have said on this page or other sites before I'm sure. This film kinda seems 'dangerously furry'. Well that's because... it is, folks. What got Disney off the ground way back in the 1920s? Animated, anthropomorphic or humanoid animals. Micky Mouse is of course one of those animated characters. Disney is going back to their roots with this film. I like that. Good on them, at least acknowledging where their fame and fortune came from, ya know? Same can be said for Warner Bros. Animation. Loony Tunes ring a bell, anyone? Same thing that was their claim to fame, anthro-animal characters since those kinds of cartoons REALLY appeal to children... that audience is the primary aim¬† of these kinds or types of films. But hey, I'll go see this if it has a modern setting and is a comedy as shown.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment:
Okay, like... I get that they're animals, and this is something I'm completely fine with, given that Disney had been making movies with talking animals since a very long time. What I don't get is... why is it suddenly relevant that the characters are animals? This trailer keeps saying "Look at how HUMAN these animals are!", as if it was trying to pass this whole anthro animal character idea as some entirely new concept that no one had ever seen before-- we are talking about Disney in here, who had been doing cartoons and movies with talking animals since the past century, and then suddenly in this trailer, they act like none of that never happened.

That being said, this trailer is overly glorifying a very generic concept for nowadays, and doesn't helps me understand what I'm supposed to be expecting from this movie, other than the fact that everyone is an animal.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment:
Wow.¬† Anthropomorphic animals.¬† Why haven't we thought of this already?¬† How much cooler would Mickey Man and Bugs Being be if they were animals endowed with speech?¬† To say nothing of Porky Person, Donald Dude, the Tasmanian Dervish, Huckleberry Human, My Little People, and countless other classic staples of animation!¬† Imagine!¬† Talking animals, it just makes everything better!

Seriously, maybe it'll be a great movie, it's coming from a solid studio, but it seems slightly weird that they're emphasizing something that's pretty well taken for granted in this day and age in all walks of fiction.¬† But maybe that's the point...¬† Maybe we should be reminded what a neat idea it is, and by addressing it directly we'll gain a new perspective!

On the other hand, saying it's like "nothing we've seen be-fur" is pretty hard to directly justify.¬† It's possible they've got some radical plot twist that'll blow our minds, but there's nothing in this trailer that hasn't been done literally millions of times before.¬† Ah, well, maybe future trailers will elaborate on that claim.¬† Not like we've got much to go on.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment: There's a lot of comments about furries. Having an internet connection and reading though lots of comments and stuff, naturally I am aware of such things. I actually have theory about furries and bronies. I think that everyone has a piece inside of them that is satisfied from social interaction. I think these are people who have for some reason lost the ability for that piece inside of them to be satisfied by other people. But furry and brony characters are characters who are like people, but they are also created to be very accessible to people with underdeveloped socialization, by design. So these characters appeal to these guys. I mean, MLP has a fanbase of people who probably large numbers of them would have trouble being completely comfortable in a normal adult relationship. Just going off the stereotype.. I could be wrong, (but am I) I've seen reviews of mlp, even tried to watch an episode (it was like the time I tried to listen to a Justin Bieber song, I couldn't make it all the way through). But in the case of MLP the characters are essentially candy colored little women (in like .. horse form .. I know .. but still) in a friendly accessible fantasy world, so is it any wonder these characters appeal to them? And since they are probably also repressed when it comes to natural sexuality, is it any wonder there is a rather prominent amount of porn dedicated to the subject as well? To me it seems like it's almost logical that it exists. And I don't really care, there's worse things to be into, it's not something I think it's healthy to be all about, it's not something that I think someone should TRY to be into, but frankly it's like eating a bad diet or playing too much video games, it's harmful to the person, but I don't think it's that harmful to others. The ironic thing is that hostile social environments I think is what ends up shaping people who go into these fanbases in the first place, so people who are angry about weird but probably harmless people are actually the ones who ironically play one of the largest roles in making them. Anyway just my theory, I wonder if I'm right or wrong.

Through out reading a lot of comments here, I am seeing some place a connection with the ongoing webcomic, Zoophobia. Yes there are reason to connect the two, one the names being similar and two, the silly pun. BUT seriously guys, this film as far as we can all tell, will strictly be about anthro's (no humans) nor will it likely revolve around a school and students (the fox appears to be the main character and he looks like he works at a office). Though Zoophobia is a cool comic and I check up on it weekly myself, I doubt a percentage of people working on this film has ever came across this comic and just figured up a title for the film sort like the author to the comic did. One placed phobia cause the main character is scared of said animals. The other Topia because its a city full of anthros.¬†
I'm super hyped about this film nonetheless and hope it has a great story plot. I've been waiting to see Disney do a anthro film again (with no humans at ALL) for quite awhile.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment: See, I have a better idea. A movie that opens up to a superhero saving the day. After a mighty battle with his enemy and a daring rescue of a little girl from radioactive doom, our yet unnamed hero returns to his home, exhausted and a mess...ew...radioactive sweaty super-underwear...atleast it's the outer pair for over his pants. ANYWAY. He casually tosses his dirty clothes in the hamper despite his wife yelling from downstairs to remember his costume goes in the special bin not the regular hamper, and he tiredly staggers off to take a shower. Welllll....when he steps out and goes to find some clean clothes for the evening, the hamper is missing. His wife screams from down stairs and as he rushes awkwardly down the stairs in his towel, he discovers a now LIVING clothes hamper monster trying to eat his wife's oven mit while she tries to wrestle the mit back. The creature panics and escapes, and soon reports of a wandering laundry monster stealing and eatting people's socks pop up all over the neighborhood. People from all walks and groups try to stop the beast, but it keep escaping. A lazy little boy discovers the hamper monster in his backyard, and finds out if he feeds the monster his dirty clothes...he doesn't have to wash them. Ever. So he decides to try and hide it and keep it as a pet, to make cleaning his room easier. Adventure, childhood pet keeping love, drama, and a few tense scenes ensue and in a dramatic battle between the hero hubby in deep doo doo and the hamper monster who mistakenly thinks he has to defend or protect the boy from the hero...the hamper breaks. All smelly missing laundry appears in a massive pile from seemingly out of no where in the middle of the road where the hamper now lay ordinary, plastic, and broken in half. The boy begins to weep. Falling to his knees and bawling, something stirs in the mountain of lost dirty clothes...a pile of baby hamper beasts no bigger than decks of cards leap up and scatter off away. People shriek but the boy is over joyed. These tiny hamper monsters move into homes all acrossed the globe, hiding behind clothes dryers and feasting on the left socks of the world.

Comment:
This trailer gets so many things wrong, it just make me cringe.¬† Let's list them, shall we?
- Right off the bat:¬† Humans *are* animals.¬† You can try and separate them all you want, but humans belong to same Kingdom Animalia as every other mammal, fish, amphibian, reptile, bird, and invertebrate.¬† Would have been better to say, "This is not a human." instead of "This is an animal."
- Anthropomorphised means "human-like" in every meaning of the word... not just "it basically walks on two legs".¬† If that were the case, then every animal that already walks on two legs is "anthropomorphic" when they plainly aren't.
- Foxes have hearing far superior to rabbits.
- Crotch-cover when mentioning clothes.¬† Nothing to see in the first place.¬† That old schtick is getting tired.¬† Not to mention, most furred animals have no need for clothes.
- Technology use:¬† Not limited to humans.¬† Many animals use tools, via trial and error, a very basic version of "the scientific method".¬†
- Ignoring the pun:¬† Something we haven't seen before... with everything you've mentioned is in this movie?¬† Ignoring, what, the dozens if not hundreds of animated features from around the world, Disney included, that feature nothing but anthropomorphic animals wearing clothes and doing human-like activities in natural conflict between their relative species?¬† I don't think so.
- Be-fur.¬† Puns.¬† No.¬† Puns are bad.¬† Especially puns that end in "fur".

I get the impression this trailer was made by a Furry... featuring all the retardation that comes with being one.  It even sounds like it was narrated by a Furry.

This movie is actually pretty adorable. The fox alone has so much expression with just his ears. Animation has come so far and I'm actually kinda excited to see what the story of this movie will be. If there even is a story. It could just be, "Let's follow a fox through his life in Zootopia."

Of course, as this is an animated movie with anthropomorphic animals in it, it will attract a huge amount of attention from Furries. We're fans of this schit, what do you expect? Some people will find an erotic niche, some will find a duplication(because replication is a sign of appreciation) niche, and others will enjoy or hate the film for their own reasons.

Some extreme furries might come in with their furry gear and get their furry all over the theater, others might come as generic moviegoers secretly stroking their affinity for anthros. And another chunk of people /will/ be generic movie goers, come to see what the movie has to offer.

A bunch of grown men and women in animal costumes are coming to theaters, in public, sitting down and masturbating in front of other people with each other."

This movie is going to attract a certain kind of people because it meets a certain kind of people's attractions and affinities. It will attract a smaller kind of people as it meets their creative desires and an even smaller amount of people as it meets their creative and sexual needs to replicate and to twist into a sexual light. Its almost guaranteed to make at least some kind of news as it will be very controversial because of the Furry following.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment:
As much as I like how this looks like its going to turn out, my only problem with it is its similarity to a comic/book called Zoophobia that has and still is being written for years by artist and animator Vivienne Medrano, who has put her heart and soul into that book.

I feel sorry for her. Since Disney is an empire in animation and motion picture industry, she can't do anything about it. I would feel terribly awful too if someone bigger and more well-known than me came along, took my idea, bent it a little and said "Hey! Look at this completely original movie I just made up myself!", while I sat in the corner with a comic I've been working on for 8 years, carefully and wholeheartedly devoting myself to, and I could do nothing to change it.

No disrespect to Disney, Zootopia, Zoophobia or Vivienne, of course.

They're not technically 'furries' just because they're animals that walk on two-feet and act like humans. Usually, furries have more human-like appearances with animal features...and, the definition of a furry is someone who feels that they have a 'fursona' of sorts. I mean, take it as you see it, but don't hate the movie if you hate furries...and don't assume that it is a 'furry movie', either. But it's not a bad thing if it were, regardless.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment: I can only hope the best for this.¬† The trailer does not give us any real scoop on the plot, if any.¬† I personally enjoyed two franchises loads of people really loved, or really hated that utilized this kind of world:¬† AATC and FiM.¬† A series in a world where high pitched, flat nosed dwarfs exist alongside other people, and another set in a world populated by cute but creepy little horses with marks on their hides.¬† The backlash against the Chipmunks was every bit as powerful as the fandom.¬† The scrutiny that Ponies continue to receive is staggering, yet that doesn't stop fictions and visual arts from being churned out on DA amongst others.¬† Will this movie be a turning point, or will it become a silly fad like the chipmunks and ponies did in two years or less? I can say one thing: It won't make me appreciate Anthro art any less, any more than EQG and AATC 2007 and 2009 made me love chipmunks and ponies any less.¬† If the story pleases me, then I will praise David Seville, Beatrice Miller and Celestia for a great film.

Title: Zootopia US Teaser Trailer
Comment: This looks great, but Disney, nothing we've ever seen "be-fur?" Bad pun aside, we have all seen this before. Disney, YOU have used anthropomorphic creatures in almost all of your movies. This concept itself, of a world made of entirely anthropomorphic animals, is also /not/ an original idea, which you seem to be attempting to pass it off as. There's this thing called the "furry community" (an actually great crowd full of good people that has an unfortunate and unjustified reputation). I'm not complaining, stories/worlds like this are great! And the furry community could definitely use some positive exposure. I just feel like it's kind of a kick in the leg to the countless people who have made stories and graphic novels like this when you say it's "like nothing seen before." Other than that little line, this seems amazing, and I'm pretty excited for it! I'd just be nice if you stopped advertising it in a way that makes it seem like you're trying to sell it as an original concept. Not sure if that was your intent or not, but that's the feeling I got from watching the trailer.

I give Disney major kudos for making a movie using the term "anthropomorphic" correctly, as well as shooting for an original anthropomorphic film period.

So I won't rain on their parade and mention PlayStation's Sly Cooper, Hanna Barbera's SWAT Kats, Nintendo's Star Fox, Dreamwork's Kung Fu Panda or Nickolodeon's Tuff Puppy.
